§I OPEN-QUESTIONS
  ⟦
    OQ.01 · should gpu<T> support being held across @gpu fn boundaries with implicit identity-transfer?
             default · yes for same-device · explicit transfer for cross-device · revisit if cross-device adds friction
    
    OQ.02 · should shared<T, NonCoherent> require the user to specify which direction (h2d vs d2h) at alloc-time?
             default · no · directionality is per-access not per-allocation · barrier-direction encodes it
    
    OQ.03 · for unified-memory targets (Apple Silicon · ARM iGPU) · do we collapse gpu<T> ≡ T at codegen?
             default · yes · zero-cost identity transfer · target-feature-query at codegen
    
    OQ.04 · how does this interact with persistent_kernel attribute (item 31 in 63_IMPROVEMENT_BACKLOG_100)?
             default · persistent-kernel sees its inputs as gpu<T> · CPU writes via shared<RingBuffer> with NonCoherent
             this is the PRISM "submit once run forever" architecture · gets the typing it needs
    
    OQ.05 · should there be a "borrow-of-gpu<T>-from-CPU-for-read-only-inspection" mode (e.g. for tools/debugger)?
             default · no · use download() · debugger gets a copy not a view · clarifies ownership
             escalation · if dev-velocity blocked · add @debug_borrow that requires Cap<DebugInspect>
    
    OQ.06 · the "transfer<T> linear-resource" constraint may conflict with concurrent error paths · how does
             panic-unwind interact with in-flight transfers?
             default · panic causes all in-flight transfers in scope to be cancelled · cancel(t) is non-linear-safe
             this needs spec-12 + spec-13 collaboration during implementation · flagged for session-1 review
    
    OQ.07 · should there be a `weak<T>` for non-owning views into gpu<T> that the GPU can read but doesn't own?
             default · NO · increases complexity · use Pony-6 caps (box/val) within the @gpu context instead
  ⟧

